    <title>Combined summary - [BIP Proposal] Limit ScriptPubkey Size &gt;= 520 Bytes Consensus.</title>
    <updated>2025-10-21T02:46:33.580152+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CALeFGL0PDjtRt2rfbY4gTkoc+5oNQ0mn_obraE7PrtHuNYFpQw@mail.gmail.com/T/#m65045bb18faeca6246f01827eecc8c3afdbe1e31" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-10-02 20:42:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>In the ongoing discussions within the Bitcoin Development Mailing List, Antoine Riard raised concerns about a proposal that aims to modify the scriptPubKey size limits within Bitcoin transactions. This proposal, while intended to clean up and optimize the network, carries a significant risk of confiscating user funds unintentionally, especially for bare multisig transactions which have historically been used within the network. Riard highlights that using uncompressed public keys in a multisig setup could easily breach the proposed size limit, making this a real issue rather than a theoretical one, as has been the case with most other cleanup proposals.
The conversation delves into the specifics of how such a rule change could inadvertently impact users who have engaged in completely standard practices, pointing out that the historical use of bare multisigs due to earlier protocol limitations might exacerbate these impacts. To mitigate these risks, Riard suggests implementing the new rules incrementally, applying them only to transactions without post-activation nLocktime or those with inputs created after the activation height. This approach would aim to unearth and address any significant confiscation risks by limiting the rule's application to new coins initially, then expanding its reach if no adverse effects are observed.
Further exploration of mitigative strategies includes tracking the &quot;maximum reorg height&quot; (MRH) for each output, which represents the highest block height within an output's causal history. This metric could help ensure that transactions are compliant with new rules based on their historical context, potentially eliminating the risk of confiscating funds through unintended consequences of the rule change. However, implementing MRH tracking would require significant modifications to existing systems, including additional data storage for each UTXO entry and a complete resync or reindex of the blockchain, introducing high costs for what Riard views as limited benefits from the proposal.
Riard expresses skepticism about the overall value of the proposed changes, considering the inherent costs and risks associated with any consensus rule modification. He argues that attempts to minimize undesirable data within the UTXO set might paradoxically increase the volume of non-prunable data on the network, as users seeking to bypass the restrictions could simply create multiple smaller outputs rather than a single large one. This scenario could lead to a greater burden on the network than the current state, despite the intentions behind the proposal.
Overall, the discussion reflects a nuanced consideration of the trade-offs involved in evolving Bitcoin's protocol, emphasizing the need for careful analysis and mitigation of potential risks to users. The dialogue also underscores the complexity of implementing consensus changes in a decentralized system, where the implications of proposed adjustments must be thoroughly understood and addressed to safeguard the network's integrity and user trust.</summary>
